Myopic vs Optimal Strategy in the Stubborn Targeting Model (fixed)¶

James Yu, 17 January 2022

In [1]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
In [2]:
def compute_L(x_0, T, R):
    A = np.array([
      [0.99 * 0.99, 0.01 * 0.99], # stubborn agent, self-loop = 0.99
      [0.5,         0.5        ], # easily-influenced agent
    ], ndmin = 2)

    B = np.array([
      [0.01],                     # target the stubborn agent
      [0]
    ], ndmin = 2)

    # default delta = 1, Q = I_n
    delta = 1
    Q = 1/2 * np.identity(2)
    
    K_t = Q
    K_sequence = [Q]
    for i in range(T):
        K_t = delta * A.T @ (K_t - K_t @ B @ np.linalg.inv(B.T @ K_t @ B + R / delta) @ B.T @ K_t) @ A + Q
        K_sequence.insert(0, K_t)
        
    L = []
    for t in range(T):
        L.append(-np.linalg.inv(B.T @ K_sequence[t+1] @ B + R / delta) @ B.T @ K_sequence[t+1] @ A)
        
    x_sequence = [x_0]
    r_sequence = []
    x_myopic = [x_0]
    r_myopic = []
    for l in L:
        r_sequence.append((l @ x_sequence[-1]).item())
        x_sequence.append((A + B @ l) @ x_sequence[-1]) 
        r_myopic.append((L[-1] @ x_myopic[-1]).item())
        x_myopic.append((A + B @ L[-1]) @ x_myopic[-1]) 
    
    return r_sequence, r_myopic, x_sequence, x_myopic

R = 0¶

Note that to start, $x_0 = [5, 100]$ i.e. the agent not being targeted is further away.

In [3]:
x_0 = np.array([
  [5],
  [100]
], ndmin = 2)

optimal, myopic, xs, xm = compute_L(x_0, 30, 0)
plt.plot(range(len(optimal)), optimal, label = "Optimal Strategy")
plt.plot(range(len(myopic)), myopic, label = "Myopic Strategy")
plt.title("Message vs Time")
plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.ylabel("Message")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [4]:
agent_0 = [x[0].item() for x in xs]
agent_1 = [x[1].item() for x in xs]
plt.plot(range(len(agent_0)), agent_0, label = "Stubborn Agent")
plt.plot(range(len(agent_1)), agent_1, label = "Easily-Influenced Agent")
plt.title("Opinions vs Time: Optimal Strategy")
plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.ylabel("Agent Opinions: Optimal Strategy")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
